    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-05-31T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-05-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="1617"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1617">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 819.77/120.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">American Minister</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-05-31">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 31, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Concerning the Hyatt and Wilcox contract and your dispatch No. 128 of May 13—the
                    Department would not object to the contract if Article VII were omitted, and
                    paragraph 5 of Article XVI, and if amended so as to conform to the
                    recommendations of the board. You will so inform the Minister for Foreign
                    Affairs, adding that if the railroad is built the United States Government would
                    like to have an understanding that it could use the railroad in case of
                    emergency, the same as the other railroads near the Canal Zone.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Knox</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
